      <hedline>
        <hl1>Facing Child Poverty</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert M Sherry letter comments on August 17 editorial on speech at Democratic National Convention by former Sen Bill Bradley, who spoke of plight of 13.5 million poor children across America</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Metropolis of Poor Children'' (editorial, Aug. 17), about Bill Bradley's speech at the Democratic National Convention:</p>
        <p>Mr. Bradley conjured up a horrifying and graphic image: that if all the 13.5 million poor children in America were gathered in one place, they would form a city bigger than New York. But the image will fade unless there are others like Mr. Bradley who are willing to stand up and point out the shame of the richest country on the planet.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Metropolis of Poor Children'' (editorial, Aug. 17), about Bill Bradley's speech at the Democratic National Convention:</p>
        <p>Mr. Bradley conjured up a horrifying and graphic image: that if all the 13.5 million poor children in America were gathered in one place, they would form a city bigger than New York. But the image will fade unless there are others like Mr. Bradley who are willing to stand up and point out the shame of the richest country on the planet.</p>
        <p>The shame is that while we have made so many improvements in basic life, a large proportion of the population has been left far behind. Until many more Americans share an overwhelming disgust for what we have not accomplished, little will change.</p>
        <p>ROBERT M. STERRY  West Linn, Ore., Aug. 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
